Aggregate Functions + GROUP BY 
Aggregate Functions + GROUP BY is used in almost every real job
---
🧠 1. Aggregate Functions (Summary Operations)
👉 These functions calculate values from multiple rows
---
🔹 Main Aggregate Functions
Function	Meaning
COUNT()	Number of rows
SUM()	            Total
AVG()	            Average
MAX()	            Highest value
MIN()	            Lowest value
---
🔹 Example Table: students
id	name	age	marks
1	Rahul	22	80
2	Amit	19	70
3	Neha	21	90
4	Ravi	22	60
---
🔹 COUNT()
SELECT COUNT(*) FROM students;
👉 Output: 4 students
---
🔹 SUM()
SELECT SUM(marks) FROM students;
---
🔹 AVG()
SELECT AVG(marks) FROM students;
---
🔹 MAX / MIN
SELECT MAX(marks), MIN(marks) FROM students;
---
⚠️ Important Rule
👉 Aggregate functions return single value (summary)
---

 2. GROUP BY (Grouping Data)
👉 GROUP BY = Group similar rows and apply aggregate
---
🔹 Basic Syntax
SELECT column, AGG_FUNCTION(column)
FROM table
GROUP BY column;
---
🔹 Example: Group by Age
SELECT age, COUNT(*) 
FROM students
GROUP BY age;

👉 Output:
age	count
19	1
21	1
22	2

---
🔹 Average Marks per Age
SELECT age, AVG(marks)
FROM students
GROUP BY age;
---
🔥 Real-Life Example
👉 Company wants:
Number of employees per department

SELECT department, COUNT(*) 
FROM employees
GROUP BY department;
---
⚠️ Common Mistake (VERY IMPORTANT)
❌ Wrong:
SELECT name, COUNT(*) FROM students;
👉 ERROR (because name is not grouped)
---
✅ Correct:
SELECT age, COUNT(*) FROM students
GROUP BY age;
---
🔥 GROUP BY + HAVING (Important Combo)
👉 HAVING = filter groups (after grouping)
---
🔹 Example: Age having more than 1 student
SELECT age, COUNT(*) 
FROM students
GROUP BY age
HAVING COUNT(*) > 1;

👉 Output:
age	count
22	2
---
🧠 WHERE vs HAVING
Feature   	WHERE	             HAVING
Use       	Before grouping	  After grouping
Works on	  Rows	            Groups
---
🔹 Example
SELECT age, COUNT(*)
FROM students
WHERE marks > 60
GROUP BY age
HAVING COUNT(*) > 1;
---
🎯 Real Interview Questions
1. Find total salary per department
2. Find average marks per class
3. Find departments with more than 5 employees
4. Find highest salary per department
---
🧪 Practice Questions
Try yourself:
1. Count students by age
2. Find average marks per age
3. Find max marks per age
4. Show ages with more than 1 student
5. Count students with marks > 70 (grouped by age)
---
💡 Final Understanding
Aggregate → gives summary
GROUP BY → divides into groups
HAVING → filters groups
---
🚀 Pro Tip (Very Important)
👉 Always remember order:
SELECT → FROM → WHERE → GROUP BY → HAVING → ORDER BY
